{"questionId":"22643","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Let the function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>)</mo></math> represent the height in centimetres of a cylindrical tin can with&nbsp;diameter <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mtext> cm</mtext></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mfenced><mi>x</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>640</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>14</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The function <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>h</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math> is the inverse function of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>In the context of the question, interpret your answer to part (b)(i).</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>a tin that is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math> high will have a diameter of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>21</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>20782</mn><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>)</mo></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Condone a correct answer expressed as the converse.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22643","referenceCode":"21N.1.SL.TZ0.5b.ii","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"In the context of the question, interpret your answer to part (b)(i).","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximu